<span class=dateline>October   21, 2003</span> - I have been quite ill and missed a few updates. I hope this makes up for it! I am combining our bi-weekly EQII Q&A and our weekly EQII Screenshot for you to enjoy. They will return to their regular schedules in the coming weeks.<BR>
<BR>
Thank you!<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<CENTER><B><BIG>EverQuest II Mini Q&A #6</BIG></B><BR>
With Steve "Moorgard" Danuser</CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Could you go into more depth about how tradeskills will work in EverQuest II?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> We have a dedicated tradeskill archetype called the Artisan. Instead of gaining experience through adventuring, Artisans advance in levels through the use of their abilities-creating items, for example. Experience isn't just earned on the final combine, but rather throughout the creation process.<BR>
<BR>
Our goal is to make tradeskills fun and challenging, not just a series of repetitive combines. To this end, tradeskills are comprised of a series of mini games that require the attention of the player and allow the end result to be consciously modified. The quality of the finished product is determined not just by a set recipe, but by a combination of the character's skill level and how good the player is at the crafting process. Just as a skilled level 20 player can defeat opponents that might give an unskilled level 25 player problems, so will the lower-level Artisan who understands the intricacies of his trade have advantages over a higher-level player who does not.<BR>
<BR>
Unlike tradeskills in EverQuest, crafting most items in EverQuest II isn't a short process. Making a single sword from raw materials to the finished product, even at low levels, can be a significant investment in time. High-level Artisans will be unlikely to take business from lower-level crafters, partly because the smaller profit won't be worth it for the time involved and partly because they won't be earning experience for doing so.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> No game to date has done really fun hand to hand combat. Can you explain, in some detail, how exactly combat will work? Beyond the being able to attack specific zones of a body. What about archery?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> Combat in EQ2 is similar to that of EverQuest in many ways, but involves more decision making on the part of melee classes. To achieve maximum effectiveness, players must choose which combat Arts to use-just as casters have to decide which spells work best in a given situation. Those choices will vary depending on the encounter and what classes the adventurer is grouped with. It will definitely be to your advantage to understand the abilities of others, as some Arts work best in combination with those of another class.<BR>
<BR>
Ranged attacks such as archery will be a more specialized form of combat. Certain classes (especially those on the Scout tree) will have access to powerful ranged combat Arts that allow for large amounts of situational damage. Such attacks won't be unlimited, however-ranged combat costs significant amounts of stamina to maintain, and stamina is a precious resource for melee classes.<BR>
<BR>
 <BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> The magic system also interests many. Could you go into more detail on exactly how this works?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> Besides mana, another resource casters will manage is Concentration. Most spells that have a duration-such as buffs, DoTs, etc.-require Concentration to maintain. This will be a finite resource, which limits the number of this type of spells that one caster can have in use at any one time. Spells will vary in their Concentration costs. Group buffs tend to use a significant amount of Concentration, while individual player buffs will have a lower cost.<BR>
<BR>
Another difference in our magic system is that many buffs will only take hold on members of the caster's group. This is designed to reinforce our idea of the "closed set" for combat that pits your group's resources against those of your opponents. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
